t: Blessed*p be the Lord*s my strength, which teacheth my hands to war, and my fingers to fight:
My*p goodness, and my fortress; my high tower, and my deliverer; my shield, and he in whom I trust; who subdueth my people under me.
Lord,*sp what is man, that thou takest knowledge of him! or the son of man, that thou makest account of him!
Man*p is like to vanity: his days are as a shadow that passeth away.
Bow*p thy heavens, O Lord,*s and come down: touch the mountains, and they shall smoke.
Cast*p forth lightning, and scatter them: shoot out thine arrows, and destroy them.
Send*p thine hand from above; rid me, and deliver me out of great waters, from the hand of strange children;
Whose*p mouth speaketh vanity, and their right hand is a right hand of falsehood.
I*p will sing a new song unto thee, O God: upon a psaltery and an instrument of ten strings will I sing praises unto thee.
It*p is he that giveth salvation unto kings: who delivereth David his servant from the hurtful sword.
Rid*p me, and deliver me from the hand of strange children, whose mouth speaketh vanity, and their right hand is a right hand of falsehood:
That*p our sons may be as plants grown up in their youth; that our daughters may be as corner stones, polished after the similitude of a palace:
That*p our garners may be full, affording all manner of store: that our sheep may bring forth thousands and ten thousands in our streets:
That*p our oxen may be strong to labour; that there be no breaking in, nor going out; that there be no complaining in our streets.
Happy*p is that people, that is in such a case: yea, happy is that people, whose God is the Lord.*s
